BACKGROUND: Prophylactic total gastrectomy (PTG) remains the only means of 
preventing gastric cancer for people with genetic mutations predisposing to 
Hereditary Diffuse Gastric Cancer (HDGC), mainly in the CDH1 gene. The small but 
growing cohort of people undergoing PTG at a young age are expected to have a 
life-expectancy close to the general population, however, knowledge of the 
long-term effects of, and monitoring requirements after, PTG is limited. This 
study aims to define the standard of care for follow-up after PTG.
METHODS: Through a combination of literature review and two-round Delphi 
consensus of major HDGC/PTG units and physicians, and patient advocates, we 
produced a set of recommendations for follow-up after PTG.
RESULTS: There were 42 first round, and 62 second round, responses from 
clinicians, allied health professionals and patient advocates. The guidelines 
include recommendations for timing of assessments and specialties involved in 
providing follow-up, micronutrient supplementation and monitoring, bone health 
and the provision of written information.
CONCLUSION: While the evidence supporting the guidelines is limited, expert 
consensus provides a framework to best manage people following PTG, and could 
support the collection of information on the long-term effects of PTG.

