Cystic fibrosis (CF) is a common disorder of autosomal recessive inheritance, 
that once conferred a life expectancy of only a few months. Over recent years, 
significant advances have been made to CF therapeutic approaches, changing the 
face of the disease, and facilitating the partial restoration of pancreatic 
function. This mini review summarizes the current landscape of exocrine 
pancreatic management in CF and explores areas for future direction and 
development.

